  <h2>How a Cash Sale Stops Foreclosure</h2>
  <p>When your home sells before the foreclosure auction, the lender gets paid off at closing and the process stops. The foreclosure never completes. Your credit takes a hit from the missed payments — there's no getting around that — but a completed foreclosure is a completely different level of damage. It stays on your record for seven years and affects your ability to buy again, rent, even get certain jobs.</p>
  <p>A sale before that point lets you exit on your own terms. You're in control of the timeline and the outcome instead of waiting for the bank to set the date.</p>

  <h2>What If You Owe More Than the House Is Worth?</h2>
  <p>This comes up more than people think. If your mortgage balance is higher than what the home will sell for, that's called being underwater — and it complicates things. A traditional sale won't work without lender approval. What sometimes does work is a short sale, where the lender agrees to accept less than what's owed.</p>
  <p>I can walk through the numbers with you honestly. If a short sale is the realistic path, I'll tell you that. If there's equity and a clean exit is possible, we can move fast. Either way, you'll know where you stand after one conversation.</p>

  <h2>What I Need From You to Help</h2>
  <p>To give you an honest picture of your options, I need to know a few things:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Where you are in the foreclosure process — notice of default, scheduled sale date, or something else</li>
    <li>Roughly what you owe on the mortgage</li>
    <li>The address and general condition of the property</li>
  </ul>
  <p>You don't need all the paperwork in front of you. Just a general picture is enough to start the conversation. I've helped people in early and late stages — the earlier the better, but late isn't hopeless either.</p>

